This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it proposes a new model for traffic speed forecasting using graph convolutional networks. It also involves training the model on large-scale real-world datasets, which is a common practice in machine learning research. 

It could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as the proposed model involves learning spatial dependencies in traffic forecasting, which is a common problem in AI research. 

The paper also involves using computer vision techniques such as graph convolutional networks, which could make it relevant to cs.CV (Computer Vision) sub-category. 

The use of graph convolutional networks to model spatial dependencies could also make it relevant to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category. 

Finally, the use of neural networks for traffic forecasting could make it relevant to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category.
